            "Military service. Congress passed The Burke-Wadsworth Selective Service Bill on September 14, 1940. Steinbeck was too old to be conscripted into active duty, and his \x{201c}radical\x{201d} past, which had become the subject of an extensive FBI file, repeatedly foiled his request for an Army officer\x{2019}s commission. (\x{201c}Do you suppose you could ask Edgar\x{2019}s boys to stop stepping on my heels? They think I\x{2019}m an enemy alien. It\x{2019}s getting tiresome,\x{201d} Steinbeck told United States Attorney General Francis Biddle, who in turn forwarded Steinbeck\x{2019}s note to FBI director J. Edgar Hoover on May 11, 1942.) Eventually Steinbeck worked under the auspices of the Office of War Information, and the Air Force, for which he wrote\x{2014}and John Swope photographed\x{2014}Bombs Away: The Story of a Bomber Team (New York: The Viking Press, 1942). In 1943 he was accredited as a war correspondent and spent June through October of that year writing dispatches from Europe and North Africa for the New York Herald Tribune, which were later collected as Once  There Was a War (New York: The Viking Press, 1958). Jackson Benson, in True Adventures of John Steinbeck (pp. 485\x{2014}541), is the first to establish the factual order and significance of Steinbeck\x{2019}s World War II activities. At J. Edgar Hoover\x{2019}s direction the FBI kept detailed files on American writers they considered subversive and dangerous. Steinbeck was no exception; the FBI monitored him from <<1939|9c:0>>, when The Grapes of Wrath first appeared, to March 1968, nine months before he  died. The chilling story is evident in Jack Sirica, \x{201c}FBI tracked Steinbeck\x{2019}s travels and friendships for nearly 30 years,\x{201d} San Jose Mercury News, June 14, 1984, pp. 1, 12A, and in Herbert Mitgang, Dangerous Dossiers: Exposing the Secret War Against America\x{2019}s Greatest Authors  (New York: Donald I. Fine, 1988) pp. 71-79.",
